Certainly! Setting up an S3 bucket using AWS CDK (Cloud Development Kit) to store customer financial records is a great way to manage your infrastructure as code. Below is an example of how you can do this securely and efficiently.

First, make sure you have the AWS CDK installed and your AWS credentials configured. You can install the AWS CDK using npm:

```sh
npm install -g aws-cdk
```

Next, create a new CDK project:

```sh
cdk init app --language=typescript
```

Then, install the necessary CDK libraries for S3:

```sh
npm install @aws-cdk/aws-s3 @aws-cdk/aws-iam
```

Now, you can create a new stack in your CDK project. Open the `lib/your-app-stack.ts` file and add the following code:

```typescript
import * as cdk from '@aws-cdk/core';
import * as s3 from '@aws-cdk/aws-s3';
import * as iam from '@aws-cdk/aws-iam';

export class YourAppStack extends cdk.Stack {
  constructor(scope: cdk.Construct, id: string, props?: cdk.StackProps) {
    super(scope, id, props);

    const bucketName = 'customer-financial-records-bucket';

    // Create the S3 bucket
    const bucket = new s3.Bucket(this, 'CustomerFinancialRecordsBucket', {
      removalPolicy: cdk.RemovalPolicy.DESTROY, // Be cautious with this in production
      blockPublicAccess: s3.BlockPublicAccess.BLOCK_ALL,
      encryption: s3.BucketEncryption.S3_MANAGED,
      versioned: true,
    });

    // Grant read/write permissions to the IAM user or role
    const bucketPolicy = new s3.BucketPolicy(this, 'BucketPolicy', {
      bucket: bucket,
      policy: bucket.addToResourcePolicy(new iam.PolicyStatement({
        actions: ['s3:GetObject', 's3:PutObject'],
        resources: [bucket.arnForObjects('*')],
        principals: [new iam.AnyPrincipal()],
      })),
    });

    // Output the bucket name
    new cdk.CfnOutput(this, 'BucketName', { value: bucket.bucketName });
  }
}
```

In this example, we create an S3 bucket with the following configurations:
- The bucket is set to be removed when the stack is deleted (`removalPolicy: cdk.RemovalPolicy.DESTROY`), which is useful for development but should be handled with care in production.
- Public access is blocked (`blockPublicAccess: s3.BlockPublicAccess.BLOCK_ALL`).
- The bucket uses S3-managed encryption.
- Versioning is enabled to keep track of changes to objects.

We also create a bucket policy that grants read and write permissions to any IAM user or role.

Finally, we output the bucket name for easy reference.

To deploy this stack, run the following command in your terminal:

```sh
cdk deploy
```

Make sure to review and adjust the bucket policy and other configurations according to your security requirements and best practices. Always avoid using `removalPolicy: cdk.RemovalPolicy.DESTROY` in production environments, as it will permanently delete the bucket and its contents. Instead, use a more controlled approach for managing resources.

